UNICEF aims to achieve this through Fostering Innovation And Use Of New Technologies, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: By 2020, adolescents and youth (girls and boys) are more resilient and have capacities and opportunities to seek and secure meaningful participation in local governance systems to influence policies, programmes, services and to transition successfully from school or NEET (adolescents and youth not in employment, education or training) to quality education and gainful employment

description.narrative: In 2020, UNICEF Kosovo in response to COVID-19 launched the Learning Passport, a Global Initiative in partnership with Microsoft and University of Cambridge. In addition, UNICEF Kosovo shifted the implementation programme approach through digitalization of its skills-based programmes to ensure adolescents and youth continue to engage during the pandemics. During 2020, UNICEF amplified the voices of young people and increased the number of U-Reporters from 5,500 to 7,200. The Activate Talks shifted to online sessions, reaching to 43,600 adolescents and young people through two editions organized during the year. | Status:Met | As-of Date:18/01/2021
